						h2(style="font-size: medium; font-weight: bold") How to validate a Credit Card Number?
						p Most credit card number can be validated using the Luhn algorithm, also known as the "modulus 10" or "mod 10" algorithm.

						//ads
						//.ad-wrapper


						hr
						h2(style="font-size: medium; font-weight: bold") The Luhn Formula:
						p The formula verifies a number against its included check digit, which is usually appended to a partial account number to generate the full account number. This number must pass the following test:
						ul
							li From the rightmost digit, which is the check digit, moving left, double the value of every second digit; if the product of this doubling operation is greater than 9 (e.g., 8 × 2 = 16), then sum the digits of the products (e.g., 16: 1 + 6 = 7, 18: 1 + 8 = 9).
							li Take the sum of all the digits.
							li If the total modulo 10 is equal to 0 (if the total ends in zero) then the number is valid according to the Luhn formula; else it is not valid.

